  "prompt": "Just found out autistic roommate\u2019s last address was a low income housing complex that help tenants get into real life, and now he is living with me?",
  "response": "It's great that you're taking the time to learn more about your roommate's background and experiences. Living with someone who has transitioned from a supportive housing situation might present some unique opportunities and challenges. Here are a few things to keep in mind:\n\n1. **Understanding:** Try to understand more about your roommate\u2019s needs and any support they might require. People with autism can have very diverse experiences and needs.\n\n2. **Communication:** Have an open and honest conversation with your roommate. Discuss any house rules, preferences, and boundaries to ensure a harmonious living situation.\n\n3. **Support:** Be supportive and patient. Transitioning from a structured environment like a supportive housing complex to a more independent living situation can be challenging.\n\n4. **Respect Privacy:** Respect your roommate's privacy and autonomy. Just because they come from a supportive background doesn't mean they should be treated differently in terms of their personal space and freedom.\n\n5. **Resources and Support Services:** Encourage your roommate to continue accessing any support services they might need, either from previous contacts or new ones in the area.\n\n6. **Shared Responsibilities:** Make sure both of you understand and agree on shared responsibilities in the living space to avoid any potential conflicts.\n\n7. **Educate Yourself:** Take the time to learn more about autism if you\u2019re not already familiar. This can help in creating a more inclusive and understanding living environment.\n\nRemember, open dialogue and empathy are key in fostering a positive and cooperative living situation.",
